eas:**\n- How similar features are implemented\n- What patterns the codebase uses\n- What testing expectations exist\n- What documentation format is expected\n\n### Phase 2: External Best Practices\n\nIf the feature involves frameworks or libraries, research best practices:\n\n```xml\n<invoke name=\"Task\">\n<parameter name=\"description\">Framework Docs Research</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"subagent_type\">wiz:research:framework-docs-researcher</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"model\">sonnet</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"prompt\">\nResearch current best practices for implementing: /Users/stefano.straus/Gits/personal/tuicommander__wt/proxy\n\nUse Context7 MCP to look up:\n- Official documentation patterns\n- Recommended approaches for 2026\n- Known pitfalls to avoid\n\nFocus on Go and TypeScript implementations.\n</parameter>\n</invoke>\n```\n\n**Context7 Usage:** See [Context7 Setup](../../shared/commands/context7-setup.md) for MCP tools to fetch current documentation for frameworks and libraries.\n\n**Additionally, for broader industry context:**\n\n```xml\n<invoke name=\"Task\">\n<parameter name=\"description\">Best Practices Research</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"subagent_type\">wiz:research:best-practices-researcher</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"model\">sonnet</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"prompt\">\nResearch industry best practices for: /Users/stefano.straus/Gits/personal/tuicommander__wt/proxy\n\nUse Context7 and WebSearch to find:\n- Industry standards and conventions\n- Community best practices (2026)\n- Common patterns from successful projects\n- Known anti-patterns to avoid\n\nFocus on Go and TypeScript implementations.\n</parameter>\n</invoke>\n```\n\n**Library Standards (when NEW dependencies needed):**\n- **TypeScript:** jest, zod, express, pino, got\n- **Go:** testify, zerolog, cobra, pgx\n- **C#:** NUnit, FluentAssertions, Serilog, MediatR\n\nSee `wiz/standards/libraries/{language}.md` for full lists. Never use libraries from \"Avoid\" lists.\n\n### Phase 3: Specification Flow Analysis\n\nSpawn the spec flow analyzer to identify gaps:\n\n```xml\n<invoke name=\"Task\">\n<parameter name=\"description\">Spec Flow Analysis</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"subagent_type\">wiz:workflow:spec-flow-analyzer</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"model\">sonnet</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"prompt\">\nAnalyze the specification for: /Users/stefano.straus/Gits/personal/tuicommander__wt/proxy\n\nIdentify:\n1. All user flows and permutations\n2. Edge cases and error scenarios\n3. Gaps in the specification\n4. Critical questions that need answers\n\nOutput a Specification Flow Analysis.\n</parameter>\n</invoke>\n```\n\n**Analysis Dimensions:**\n\n| Dimension | Consider |\n|-----------|----------|\n| User types | Admin, regular user, API consumer |\n| Entry points | Direct, navigation, deep link, API |\n| Error scenarios | Invalid input, timeout, conflict, auth failure |\n| Data states | Empty, single, many, max limit |\n\n### Phase 4: Interactive Clarification (When Needed)\n\nWhen research reveals ambiguity or multiple valid approaches, use `AskUserQuestion` tool for structured clarification **before** generating the plan.\n\n**Trigger Conditions:**\n- Research found 2-4 viable approaches with trade-offs\n- Key architectural decision required\n- Scope is unclear (minimal vs comprehensive)\n- Technology choice impacts implementation significantly\n\n**IMPORTANT: Always recommend one option and explain why others are less suitable.**\n\nBased on codebase exploration (Phase 0.5) and research, present options with:\n1. **Recommended option** - marked with \"(Recommended)\" and listed first\n2. **Why recommended** - tie to patterns found in exploration\n3. **Why not others** - brief cons in each option's description\n\n**Example - Architecture Decision:**\n\n```\nAskUserQuestion:\n  question: \"The codebase has mixed patterns. Which approach should we follow?\"\n  header: \"Approach\"\n  options:\n    - label: \"Follow v2 pattern (Recommended)\"\n      description: \"Aligns with newer code in src/api/v2/. Con: less test coverage\"\n    - label: \"Follow v1 pattern\"\n      description: \"More tests, but older conventions. Con: inconsistent with recent work\"\n    - label: \"New unified pattern\"\n      description: \"Clean design. Con: requires migration, higher risk\"\n  multiSelect: false\n```\n\n**Example - Scope Decision:**\n\n```\nAskUserQuestion:\n  question: \"What level of implementation do you need?\"\n  header: \"Scope\"\n  options:\n    - label: \"Minimal (Recommended)\"\n      description: \"Core functionality only. Con: may need iteration later\"\n    - label: \"Standard\"\n      description: \"Common features included. Con: longer implementation\"\n    - label: \"Comprehensive\"\n      description: \"Full feature set. Con: risk of over-engineering\"\n  multiSelect: false\n```\n\n**Key principle:** You have the context from exploration - guide the user's decision, don't just present options neutrally.\n\n### Phase 5: Confident Synthesis (Conditional)\n\n**Automatically spawn confident-synthesizer agent when ANY of these criteria are met:**\n\n1. **Conflicting Recommendations** - Research agents returned contradictory approaches\n   - Example: Framework docs recommend Pattern A, but repo analysis shows Pattern B in use\n\n2. **Multiple Competing Technologies** - Two or more viable technology choices identified\n   - Example: REST vs GraphQL, Redis vs Memcached, PostgreSQL vs MongoDB\n\n3. **High-Stakes Markers** - Feature description or research contains keywords indicating critical decisions:\n   - Keywords: \"critical\", \"production\", \"security-sensitive\", \"authentication\", \"payment\", \"data integrity\"\n   - Impact areas: user data, financial transactions, access control\n\n4. **Multi-Component Architectural Decision** - Change affects 3+ components or layers\n   - Example: Adding authentication affects API, database, frontend, middleware\n\n**If criteria are met, spawn the confident-synthesizer agent:**\n\n```xml\n<invoke name=\"Task\">\n<parameter name=\"description\">Confident Synthesis</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"subagent_type\">wiz:workflow:confident-synthesizer</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"model\">sonnet</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"prompt\">\nApply confident synthesis methodology to research findings\n\nContext:\n- Repository research from Phase 1\n- External best practices from Phase 2\n- Specification analysis from Phase 3\n\nResearch outputs to synthesize:\n[List specific research findings that need synthesis]\n\nConflicting points to resolve:\n[Enumerate specific conflicts or ambiguities]\n\nDecision criteria for this feature:\n- Performance requirements\n- Security requirements\n- Maintainability requirements\n- Team expertise constraints\n\nOutput: Synthesis Report with confidence scores, recommendation, and risk assessment.\n</parameter>\n</invoke>\n```\n\nSee [confident-synthesizer](../../agents/workflow/confident-synthesizer.md) for full methodology.\n\n**If confidence < 0.6:** Additional research required.\n\n**Skip this phase if:**\n- Feature is straightforward with clear precedent\n- Research findings are consistent and unambiguous\n- Time constraints require faster planning\n\n### Phase 6: Plan Generation\n\nBased on research, clarification, and synthesis (if performed), generate the implementation plan.\n\n---\n\n## Detail Levels\n\n| Level | Content |\n|-------|---------|\n| MINIMAL | High-level steps, key decisions, critical dependencies |\n| MORE (default) | Detailed steps, file-by-file changes, test cases, acceptance criteria |\n| A LOT | Line-by-line guidance, all edge cases, complete test specs, perf/security items |\n\n---\n\n## Resume Mode\n\nIf `/Users/stefano.straus/Gits/personal/tuicommander__wt/proxy` is a path to an existing plan file (e.g. `plans/my-feature.md`), this is a **resume**:\n\n1. Read the plan file\n2. Assess current status — what phases are done, what remains\n3. Continue from where it left off\n4. Do NOT restart research if findings are already documented\n\n## Plan Tracking\n\nAfter saving the plan file, register it as the active plan:\n\n```bash\nnode $WIZ_SCRIPTS/plan-tracker.js set \"plans/<filename>.md\"\n```\n\nWhen a plan is completed (via `/wiz:work` or manually), clear the tracker:\n\n```bash\nnode $WIZ_SCRIPTS/plan-tracker.js clear\n```\n\n## Context Cleanup\n\nAfter saving the plan and setting the tracker, if context usage is **above 55%**, suggest to the user:\n\n> The plan is saved and tracked. Context is at X% — recommend running `/clear` to free context. The plan will be detected automatically on restart and you can resume with `/wiz:plan plans/<filename>.md`.\n\nDo NOT auto-clear. Always let the user decide.\n\n## Plan Output Format\n\nSave the plan to `plans/<issue_title>.md`:\n\n```markdown\n# Implementation Plan: [Feature Title]\n\n**Created:** [Date]\n**Status:** Draft\n**Estimated Effort:** [T-shirt size: XS/S/M/L/XL]\n\n## Summary\n\n[1-2 paragraph description of what will be built]\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Repository Patterns\n[Summary of relevant patterns found in codebase]\n\n### Best Practices\n[Key insights from framework documentation]\n\n### Gaps Identified\n[Missing specifications or unclear requirements]\n\n## Questions to Resolve\n\n**Risk Classification:** Use the standardized priority system for feature risk assessment. See [Priority Levels](../../shared/commands/priority-levels.md#planning-context) for P1/P2/P3 definitions.\n\n### Critical (P1 - Blockers)\n1. [Question] - [Suggested default if no answer]\n\n### Important (P2 - Affects implementation)\n2. [Question]\n\n## Implementation Order (TDD)\n\n**This section defines execution order.** `/wiz:work` executes steps in the sequence below. Each step follows red-green-refactor: write failing test → implement → refactor.\n\n### Step 1: [Component/Layer name]\n- **Test:** `path/to/component_test.ext` - [What the test verifies]\n- **Implement:** `path/to/component.ext` - [What to build]\n- **Validation:** [How to confirm this step is green]\n\n### Step 2: [Component/Layer name]\n- **Test:** `path/to/next_test.ext` - [What the test verifies]\n- **Implement:** `path/to/next.ext` - [What to build]\n- **Depends on:** Step 1\n- **Validation:** [How to confirm this step is green]\n\n### Step N: [Integration/Wiring]\n- **Test:** `path/to/integration_test.ext` - [End-to-end scenario]\n- **Implement:** `path/to/wiring.ext` - [Wire components together]\n- **Depends on:** Steps 1..N-1\n- **Validation:** Full test suite passes\n\n### Final: Documentation & Cleanup\n- [ ] Update README/docs if needed\n- [ ] Remove TODOs\n- **Validation:** Lint clean, all tests pass\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] [Measurable outcome 1]\n- [ ] [Measurable outcome 2]\n- [ ] [All tests passing]\n\n## Security Considerations\n\n[Any security implications identified]\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n[Any performance implications identified]\n\n## Related Files\n\n[List of files that will be touched]\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\nWhen ready to implement, run:\n- `/wiz:work plans/[this-file].md` - Execute the plan\n- `/wiz:deepen-plan` - Get more detail on specific sections\n- `/wiz:brainstorming` - discuss the plan details\n```\n\n## Example Usage\n\n**User Input:**\n```\n/wiz:plan Add rate limiting to our API endpoints\n```\n\n**Research Phase:**\n1. Analyze existing middleware patterns in codebase\n2. Look up rate limiting best practices for Go (gin/echo) or TypeScript (express/fastify)\n3. Identify all endpoints that need protection\n4. Analyze current auth/middleware chain\n\n**Output:**\n- `plans/api-rate-limiting.md` with complete implementation plan\n\n## Integration with Agents\n\nThis command orchestrates multiple agents:\n\n| Agent | Purpose |\n|-------|---------|\n| `Explore` | Codebase exploration before research (Phase 0.5) |\n| `repo-research-researcher` | Understand codebase patterns |\n| `framework-docs-researcher` | External documentation lookup |\n| `best-practices-researcher` | Industry patterns and standards |\n| `spec-flow-analyzer` | Gap and flow analysis |\n\n\n## Error Handling\n\n| Situation | Action |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Vague request | Use `AskUserQuestion` with 2-4 options (>4 options → text discussion) |\n| Research agent fails | Flag as \"needs research\" or use `/wiz:deepen-plan` with Context7 |\n| Conflicting patterns | Recommend newer pattern, document inconsistency for cleanup |\n\n\n## CRITICAL\n\n**NEVER CODE!**\n\nThis command is for research and planning ONLY. Do not:\n- Write implementation code\n- Create source files\n- Modify existing code\n\nThe output is a plan document. Implementation happens with `/wiz:work`.",
